, Picardie, France":"Moreuil, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"D'Encre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Herta.","English (Kent): variant of <b>Dench</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle English <i>denshe</i>, <i>dench</i> ‘Danish’ (Old English <i>denisc</i>). There were many Danes in England in the Middle Ages, not only the long-established settlers in the Danelaw region, but also more recent immigrants."],"variants":[{"name":"Denmark","meanings":["English (Norfolk): ethnic name denoting someone from Denmark (see   Dence  ). In the British Isles this name is found mainly in East Anglia.","Americanized form of German <b>Dennemark</b>, ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle Low German <i>Dennemarken</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henri D'Encre was born in 1232, his father, Gauthier D'Encre-de Moreuil, was 34 and his mother, Isabeau de Moreuil-de Daours, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Aglae DE BUS. He died in 1289, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1232–1289":"1232–1289","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1229–1274":"1229–1274","1244–1299":"1244–1299","1259–1311":"1259–1311","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1211–1268":"1211–1268","1198":"1198","1274":"1274","1259"